  <static seed="1359" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions2.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{st^{2}}{8u}}}{{\frac{s}{4tu}}}=}</m><fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{t^{3}}{2}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{st^{2}}{8u}}}{{\frac{s}{4tu}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{st^{2}}{8u}}</m> and <m>{\frac{s}{4tu}}</m>, which is <m>{8tu}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{st^{2}}{8u}}}{{\frac{s}{4tu}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{st^{2}}{8u}}\cdot{8tu}}{{\frac{s}{4tu}}\cdot{8tu}} \\
    \amp = {\frac{t^{3}}{2}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Note that you are not required to enter lost domain conditions in this problem, but it<rsq/>s good to know the following.</p>
<p>Since <m>t</m> and <m>u</m> were canceled, <m>t \ne 0</m> and <m>u \ne 0</m> are in the lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
